  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2722<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 3:01:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> I think the powers that be are on our side and always have been. They are just afraid of the public and are treading carefully. The fact that they are becoming more openly supportive suggests they know something is different. I think the public is coming on side. Chernobyl tapped into the fears laid by Hiroshima, Nagasaki and countless B-Grade movies but it wasn't followed up by other major catastrophes as was prophesised by the anti-technology druids. People are gradually accepting nuclear power and they know chemical rockets are useless for space. I think they are ready to listen to the experts and have had enough of listening to ecowackie kooks. I just know something big is coming. It's always quiet like this before a storm. Good news keeps arriving in bucketloads but most people are still unaware of Nasa's change in direction. I feel Nasa is going to make a big announcement real soon. Everything up to now has just been 'testing the water' so to speak. We shall see. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1655<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 9:37:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> FoxNews ran a special on the 30th anniversary of the last manned mission to the moon - Apollo 17 - last night.  At the end of the program they theorized about a manned mission to Mars... had an interview with  Franklin R. Chang Díaz and the program claimed that VASMIR powered spacecraft could travel from Earth to Mars in 39 days. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 10:46:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Yes, I watched that show, it was heart-wrenching and hopeful all at the same time.<br>
<br>
Of course, the guy advocating VASIMIR did not mention how we were going to get it into orbit in the first place.... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1657<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/16/02 3:41:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> I thought it would be placed in orbit by the Liberty Ship?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <br>
<br>
Anyway, good point... no one seems to address the issue of a HLV anymore...  I'm sure if one was built, a market would develop to utilize it.  Oh what sad times we live in. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2729<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 3:06:14 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Did they mention that atleast 3 nuclear reactors would be required to power VASIMR for a Mars mission? I guess not, otherwise you would have mentioned it. If the public thinks solar panels can be lifted to orbit along with VASIMR then they are being misled. <br>
<br>
What if VASIMR was somehow lifted by multiple launches and given the ISS solar panels? Would those aging cells be enough to power the plasma engine? I somehow doubt anything smaller than a football stadium could collect enough of the diminished light radiation reaching Mars from our distant sun. VASIMR would be a very nuclear spacecraft. If it even worked yet. There's still quite a bit of development to do. It might not even work at all. It's a hotter chemical rocket and must stay hot to keep its performance optimised. Regular chemical rockets are unreliable because of combustion problems. Fireworks sometimes fizzle or fly apart. VASIMR is a lot hotter. That makes it even more unreliable. If it takes 3 reactors for a practical mission and the plasma side of things goes awry then it won't be chemical drives that are blamed by Gagnon. He'll use it as an excuse to attack the reactors involved.<br>
<br>
We should just go with NTR. It's a lot simpler. One reactor and no plasma problems. Use a scramjet with chemical rocket configuration to gain maximum altitude possible then switch over to nuke power for final ascent to deep space. A single stage rocket to orbit. It's a Mars mission in one shot. Simple, clean, easy and doable right now. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A> at: 12/18/02 3:10:20 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1665<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/18/02 5:00:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> No, they didn't mention the word 'nuclear' at all.  I wasn't too surprised though.<br>
At least important people like Zubrin realize the advantages of Nuclear power<br>
in space applications.  It won't be too much longer before public<br>
opinion sways our way (I hope).  We have to keep up our web presence<br>
and branch out into other areas too... we need to preach to someone<br>
other than the choir too... I think the ad at spacedaily will go along<br>
ways... I will email them and ask how big is too big for a banner. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2734<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/19/02 11:50:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Well, discussions at the Mars Society forums are going well. Some educated and open minded visitors there. Very polite and well informed. Amenable to nuclear power too. Especially when you quote articles written by Mr Zubrin. It would be nice if we could get some high profile visitors like him or others to the board. Scientists, sci-fi writers. Perhaps we could get an interview with one. Bruce might be interested in trying Robert Zubrin. He would likely appreciate the publicity for his ideas concerning nuclear powered manned missions. Likewise we would benefit from the story. Zubrin has quite a following of supporters.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/24/02 2:48:22 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Over at newmars.com, we've been throwing around the idea of space elevators around a lot.  My view was that if we could assemble nuclear ships in orbit, you'd get around the whole issue of public dissent.  <br>
<br>
I'm not really educated in rocket engineering...so my question is, is there any kind of fuel that could be used for nuclear power that the public would find less threatening than plutonium or uranium?  Would the fuel be the same kind you could use in a nuclear weapon? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mauk2>Mauk2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/25/02 11:37:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Zentrander: The stable half of the metastable Americium-242 has VERY attractive fissile qualities for nuclear propulsion, and is not well known at all.<br>
<br>
That said, Am-242 is well written up as an actinide poison.  Hrrrrrmmmm...<br>
<br>
Plus, I am not certain what the supply is like, or what proliferation issues there are.  <br>
<br>
I think sticking to good old Uranium is our best bet.  Plutonium has that bad &quot;ooooh, bombs!&quot; thing going on, while Uranium lights up a lot of homes.  Plus, U233 is pretty darn good stuff, can be made in huge amounts if need be, and is easy to &quot;spike&quot; so it is hard to make into bombs. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2762<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/28/02 1:56:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Thorium might be even better than Uranium but I only have a sketchy appreciation of it. Some reactor designs have been put forward which are a lot safer than U233, in fact virtually foolproof from a commercial power perspective, but whether that safety can be carried over to space engines is beyond me. It's a good question you've raised and one we've discussed in the past but I think it deserves far more attention than we've given it. Getting any kind of nuclear rocket launched would be a foot in the door for nuclear launcher development. If a rocket could be proven 100% safe and reliable then the public would have no argument against it. The wildest most impossible nightmare scenario fantasies of our opposition could be waved away with a curt &quot;Couldn't happen.&quot;<br>
A perfectly safe engine is a tough ask. Nothing is totally foolproof. I think a savage reduction in efficiency would be worth the trade off though. As I say, it would be a start, and even the most critically weakened nuclear rocket crammed full of safety systems would probably be atleast 50% better than a chemical booster for payload capacity. We need research. At the moment everybody in this field is focussed on in space only concepts such as the nuclear electric rocket. Even suggesting research for launchers can get you crucified, drawn and quartered before being fed to the vultures. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 17<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/28/02 7:27:17 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> if we could make a safe nuclear engine, the public might be sufficiently appeased to allow for more risky, more efficient designs, that are still safe, but not quite on the absolute &quot;couldnt happen&quot; level, if you follow me. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1712<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/28/02 6:22:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/user/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> I don't think there are any major problems to overcome in making<br>
a safe nuclear rocket... the biggest problem will be the Public<br>
Relations effort.  The easiest sale to the general public would<br>
be a space use only nuclear rocket though. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2767<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/29/02 9:57:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> I don't know. If it was perfectly safe then it could probably be sold to the masses. Ofcourse, the ecowacky fringe will find something to whine about, but it wouldn't matter. Not if every claim is countered as invalid and laughable. They will be forced to fall back on gutter science. At that point people will stop listening. The majority atleast. To make it perfectly safe there would have to be zero possibility of fuel escaping into the environment. We cannot eliminate the possibility of a crash but ensuring the nuclear power source survives intact seems a reasonable challenge to me. What if, instead of one large uranium reactor we use a lot of smaller ones. The possibility of more than one going bad is negligible. I know that the Mauk2 has multiple nuclear thrusters. A single small reactor would be comparatively simple to deal with in the event of failure. The rocket only has to reach space. Once out of our environment it could jettison the bad engine into space. Even send it on a trajectory to hit the sun.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuclaeon>Nuclaeon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 13<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(12/30/02 1:20:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> &quot;I don't know. If it was perfectly safe then it could probably be sold to the masses. Ofcourse, the ecowacky fringe will find something to whine about, but it wouldn't matter. Not if every claim is countered as invalid and laughable. They will be forced to fall back on gutter science. At that point people will stop listening. The majority atleast.&quot;<br>
<br>
Don't underestimate human studipitity among the masses.  Either way, I think the solution begins with grassroots education about the truth of nuclear energy.  Yes, there are risks.  However, so does everything else.  At least with nuclear, you can minimize the risks. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2790<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/1/03 10:39:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: NASA considers nuclear boosters for space rockets.</span><hr size=1> Thats why I started the movement. An informed public is our mission goal. A tough one. I feel sometimes that our efforts are like a drop in the ocean but atleast we are trying. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=212.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=212.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=212.topic&index=18><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.emailToFriend?topicID=212.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a 